00:42:15.320 --> 00:42:22.619
&gt;&gt;man in audience#1: Hi. I noticed that you
didn't mention anything about the topic of

00:42:22.619 --> 00:42:29.520
energy. Obviously it's important questions,
I'm wondering why he skipped that. You know,

00:42:29.520 --> 00:42:34.670
if you have bacteria in a petri dish and a
supply of energy you will see growth. And

00:42:34.670 --> 00:42:40.349
a lot of the charts you showed for progress--if
you plot progress--some measure of progress

00:42:40.349 --> 00:42:45.460
as a present danger of availability of cheap
energy, some of the commentators have said

00:42:45.460 --> 00:42:51.760
that is actually falling if you plot GDP versus
available resources in terms of oil or whatever.

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:55.710
Ridley: Yeah, yeah. It's a very good question
and in the longer version of this talk I do

00:42:55.710 --> 00:43:01.420
have some charts on energy. You are absolutely
right, cheap energy made this possible. The

00:43:01.420 --> 00:43:05.630
reason the last 200 years have been so good--we
had improvements before that--but the last

00:43:05.630 --> 00:43:11.619
200 years have been so good because the inexhaustible
fossil fuels that did not get more expensive

00:43:11.619 --> 00:43:17.589
the more you used them like wood did, like
charcoal did, coal in particular came along

00:43:17.589 --> 00:43:22.559
in the industrial Industrial Revolution in
Britain. It turned out there were--as it were--limitless

00:43:22.559 --> 00:43:27.530
supplies of coal at the same price and eventually
the price even fell for most. So, yes cheap

00:43:27.530 --> 00:43:32.079
energy makes all the difference. And each
of us sitting here today consumes the equivalent

00:43:32.079 --> 00:43:40.079
in fossil fuel energy or at least electricity
and other kinds of energy of having roughly

00:43:40.079 --> 00:43:47.900
600 slaves in the back room on exercise bicycles
working for us. Which was how you had a rich

00:43:47.900 --> 00:43:51.220
lifestyle if you were a Bronze Age emperor
of course. You actually literally had the

00:43:51.220 --> 00:43:53.680
600 slaves working for you.

00:43:53.680 --> 00:43:59.740
So, in that sense I think the appearance of
cheap energy has made an enormous impact on

00:43:59.740 --> 00:44:06.539
our lives. And enabled us to work for each
other in a way that doesn't involve the exploitation

00:44:06.539 --> 00:44:10.680
of people to the same extent. So that's one
point. But the second point is will it all

00:44:10.680 --> 00:44:19.119
run out? Will all come grinding to a halt
very soon? And I think in terms of the three

00:44:19.119 --> 00:44:27.019
big sources of fossil fuels: coal, oil, and
gas which give us about 88% of the world's

00:44:27.019 --> 00:44:33.231
energy use at the moment. Therefore, they're
the big ones to talk about. There's no question

00:44:33.231 --> 00:44:37.140
that there's enough coal to last for many
centuries yet. It's simply a matter of how

00:44:37.140 --> 00:44:40.990
deep you dig. And there are all sorts of ways
coming on stream for getting down to deeper

00:44:40.990 --> 00:44:44.460
seams of coal and getting gas out of them
rather than having to dig out the coal themselves.

00:44:44.460 --> 00:44:51.010
So, I don't think there's any chance of running
out of coal. At least not before we've invented

00:44:51.010 --> 00:44:52.390
things to take its place.

00:44:52.390 --> 00:44:57.099
Gas had looked a little more finite until
a few years ago. The shale gas revolution

00:44:57.099 --> 00:45:01.029
that has transformed the United States gas
supplies is quite extraordinary. In the last

00:45:01.029 --> 00:45:07.180
five or 10 years America has gone from thinking
it had about 20 to 30 years of gas left to

00:45:07.180 --> 00:45:13.490
realizing it's probably got 50 to 150 years
of gas left, because of the ability to get

00:45:13.490 --> 00:45:17.740
gas outs of shale. And that's a relatively
cheap technology, and now they're trying it

00:45:17.740 --> 00:45:21.851
in Europe and they're expecting to find huge
reserves of the stuff in China too. So it's

00:45:21.851 --> 00:45:26.359
not looking like gas is going to run out anytime
soon. And by the way gas is a low carbon fuel

00:45:26.359 --> 00:45:33.420
compared with coal and oil. CH4, you're burning
a lot more hydrogen than carbon when you burn

00:45:33.420 --> 00:45:34.420
it.

00:45:34.420 --> 00:45:37.510
Oil looks more finite. It looks like were
going to run out of oil a lot sooner than

00:45:37.510 --> 00:45:43.130
we are of the others. Not literally runs out
because there are huge reserves of very expensive

00:45:43.130 --> 00:45:49.460
forms of oil like the tar sands in Alberta
and so on. They really will last 100-200 years

00:45:49.460 --> 00:45:54.619
at some point but at a price. And I think
there is no question, at some point we are

00:45:54.619 --> 00:46:02.349
likely to see oil getting more and more expensive.
The question is will that actually start to

00:46:02.349 --> 00:46:10.849
pinch off human living standards before we
have invented cheap alternatives? And I don't

00:46:10.849 --> 00:46:16.359
think it will because I think for a start
you can substitute cheap gas for a lot of

00:46:16.359 --> 00:46:22.829
the uses of oil. You can make petroleum out
of coal if necessary. You know, we're leaving

00:46:22.829 --> 00:46:26.770
aside the sort of climate consequences to
all of this. I'm just talking about the costs

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:34.799
of energy. So I rather support what, I've
forgotten his name, the guy who's just written

00:46:34.799 --> 00:46:38.359
a book called Power Hungry. It says--which
is--this century is going to be "N2N", as

00:46:38.359 --> 00:46:47.779
he calls, it natural to gas and nuclear. That's
sort of the--the source of most of our energy

00:46:47.779 --> 00:46:55.460
in this century. Long answer, good question.
Thanks for the question.

00:46:55.460 --> 00:47:01.811
&gt;&gt;man in audience #2: You had a good statistic
on homicide rates, but I'm curious about wars.

00:47:01.811 --> 00:47:06.829
Do you have any statistics on say, you know,
per capita the number of people that die in

00:47:06.829 --> 00:47:07.829
wars?

00:47:07.829 --> 00:47:12.029
&gt;&gt;Matt Ridley: Yeah, that's a really good
question. The answer is, you know the 20th

00:47:12.029 --> 00:47:19.369
century deaths per capita in wars were bad.
I don't need to tell you that you already

00:47:19.369 --> 00:47:24.819
knew that. 200 million people killed in wars
in the 20th century compared with many fewer

00:47:24.819 --> 00:47:29.519
in the 19th century. But nearly all of that
happened in the first half of the 20th century.

00:47:29.519 --> 00:47:32.680
There were about 20 million people killed
in wars in the second half of the century

00:47:32.680 --> 00:47:39.480
about 180 million in the first half. So, you
know, we went to a very very bad 50-year patch.

00:47:39.480 --> 00:47:47.460
But even if you take that 50 years and you
say this is your probability of dying in war.

00:47:47.460 --> 00:47:52.370
It was roughly 1/10 of your probability of
dying in war you lived in a hunter gatherer

00:47:52.370 --> 00:48:00.510
society in Brazil or Papua New Guinea. Hunter-gatherer
warfare is a low grade thing with a lot of

00:48:00.510 --> 00:48:05.569
skirmishing and a lot of posturing and the
odd throwing of things that results in a surprisingly

00:48:05.569 --> 00:48:10.410
large number of deaths per head of population,
even compared with industrialized warfare

00:48:10.410 --> 00:48:16.930
in the 20th century. So yeah, by 1950 the
trend had got a lot worse on wars over the

00:48:16.930 --> 00:48:20.700
last couple of hundred years. It looks like
it's gotten a lot better again in the last

00:48:20.700 --> 00:48:26.059
50 years. Which we will go in this century
I don't know. But it's a you know, it's wise

00:48:26.059 --> 00:48:29.609
to be cautious, about that I agree.

00:48:29.609 --> 00:48:35.690
&gt;&gt;man in audience #3: Do we have time for
one more question...

00:48:35.690 --> 00:48:41.990
&gt;&gt;man in audience #3: You say you're an optimist's,
but do you functioned as a futurist as well.

00:48:41.990 --> 00:48:44.599
Do you subscribe to the singularity or anything
like this?

00:48:44.599 --> 00:48:48.849
&gt;&gt;Matt Ridley: Well, it's a good question,
and I'm looking at Stephen because we were

00:48:48.849 --> 00:48:56.440
talking about this earlier. And the answer
is that I kind of duck that at the end of

00:48:56.440 --> 00:49:01.529
the book. In other words, I say I don't see
any reason why these good things can't continue

00:49:01.529 --> 00:49:06.819
but I'm not going to try specify what the
future's going to look like. Why? Because

00:49:06.819 --> 00:49:11.339
every futurologists I've ever read is looks
awfully silly 50 years later. I hope that's

00:49:11.339 --> 00:49:16.680
not true of Ray Kurzweil and people like that.
But if you look at HG Wells or Isaac Asimov

00:49:16.680 --> 00:49:21.460
or George Orwell or anything, you know, Aldous
Huxley

00:49:21.460 --> 00:49:25.019
they're writing about their own time. They're
not writing about the future actually. So

00:49:25.019 --> 00:49:30.320
for example the 1950s everyone predicted by
now we would have an incredible transport

00:49:30.320 --> 00:49:36.450
revolution. We'd all have personal gyrocopter's
and space travel would be routine and supersonic

00:49:36.450 --> 00:49:40.069
aircraft would be routine. They were completely
wrong about that transport in the turned out

00:49:40.069 --> 00:49:45.380
to be a technology that stagnate in terms
of rate of speed of transport.

00:49:45.380 --> 00:49:48.809
&gt;&gt;man in audience #4: And what about the information
explosion?

00:49:48.809 --> 00:49:54.559
Ridley: Exactly, and what they didn't spot
was that communication was going to have this

00:49:54.559 --> 00:50:01.900
explosion. So I feel at some point this communication
revolution will run out of steam as the transport

00:50:01.900 --> 00:50:07.130
one did. Steam is wrong word but you know
what I mean. Some time around the middle of

00:50:07.130 --> 00:50:14.539
this century, perhaps. But by than some other
technology will be expanding rapidly. I don't

00:50:14.539 --> 00:50:21.390
know what it will be. It'll probably be biotech
or something related to biology. But all I

00:50:21.390 --> 00:50:27.549
know is that as Yogi Berra, the baseball player,
was supposed to have once said, "I never make

00:50:27.549 --> 00:50:29.250
predictions especially about future."

